INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ee0daa73-b282-4337-865e-383cccb28497',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Ansible IaC Philosophy — Reproducibility, Drift, and Why Idempotency Is the Point$escape$,
  $escape$Ansible's IaC value isn't automation speed — it's guaranteed state. Every task in a playbook is idempotent by contract: `ansible.builtin.user`, `ansible.builtin.copy`, `ansible.builtin.systemd` only change what differs from the declared state. Run the same playbook 10 times; the 2nd through 10th runs are no-ops if nothing drifted.

Drift detection is built into `--check` mode. Combined with `--diff`, you get a line-level delta of what the live system diverged from your source-of-truth inventory and roles — without applying anything. Pair this with a scheduled CI job (`ansible-playbook --check`) and you have continuous compliance auditing.

Auditability comes from the playbook itself: tasks are declarative prose, not imperative scripts. `changed_when` and `failed_when` make outcomes explicit. Every role in `requirements.yml` is pinned by version, so a `galaxy install` from six months ago produces the same role tree today.

The key discipline: never SSH and fix manually. Every remediation goes through the playbook. If the playbook can't express it, that's a gap to close in your roles — not a one-off exception.$escape$,
  $escape$# scheduled drift detection — runs in CI without applying changes
- name: Detect configuration drift
  hosts: production
  gather_facts: true

  roles:
    - role: hardening
    - role: app_config

# CI invocation (GitHub Actions, etc.)
# ansible-playbook site.yml --check --diff \
#   -i inventories/production/hosts.yml \
#   --vault-password-file .vault_pass
#
# Exit code 0 = no drift. Non-zero = drift found → alert or open ticket.$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
